[[File:Shinsen_002.jpg|thumb|271x271px|Sake offered on {{Interlanguage link|link=Mikata|prefix=ja|foreign=三方_(神道)}}]] {{ill|Omiki|ja|神酒}} {{Nihongo|2=お神酒}} is an offering of [[sake]] or other [[alcoholic drink|alcoholic drinks]] offered to [[Kami|god]]s in Japanese [[Shinto]].<ref name="Bocking2005" /><ref>{{Cite web|last=字通|first=精選版 日本国語大辞典,デジタル大辞泉,普及版|title=神酒とは|url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E7%A5%9E%E9%85%92-537696|access-date=2022-02-26|website=コトバンク|language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=神酒(おみき)とは何？ Weblio辞書|url=https://www.weblio.jp/content/%E7%A5%9E%E9%85%92|access-date=2022-02-26|website=www.weblio.jp}}</ref>
[[Sake]] is often consumed as part of [[Shinto]] purification rituals.<ref name="Kasulis2004">{{cite book |author=Thomas P. Kasulis |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yQPWNilhjPcC&pg=PT70 |title=Shinto |date=August 2004 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |isbn=978-0-8248-6430-9 |page=70}}</ref> Sakes served to gods as offerings prior to drinking are called Omiki or Miki (お神酒, 神酒).<ref name="Bocking2005">{{cite book |author=Brian Bocking |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MWGQAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT175 |title=A Popular Dictionary of Shinto |date=30 September 2005 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-135-79738-6 |page=175}}</ref> People drink Omiki with gods to communicate with them and to solicit rich harvests the following year.
== Overview == The word "miki" is a beautiful name for sake, with "o" (mi) added to "sake". The word "miki" is a beautiful name for sake{{Citation needed|date=February 2022}}. There is a word for "comb" in [[Kojiki]], and a word for "ugus" in [[Okinawa Prefecture]]{{Citation needed|date=February 2022}}. These are connected to the word "kushi", which is due to the fact that the effects of sake were considered to be auspicious{{Citation needed|date=February 2022}}.
Sake is an essential part of [[Shinsen]], and is offered to the gods during the rituals.<ref name="f10">[[Shinsen#国学院|日本の食とこころ]] P.10</ref> The meaning of this ceremony is to receive the sake that has been offered to the gods and in which the spirit resides, and to eat and drink the same food as the gods as well as other food offerings{{Citation needed|date=February 2022}}. There are also shrines where sake is served after worshipping for two years.{{Citation needed|date=February 2022}}
Some breweries offer new sake to the [[Kamidana]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2022}}
== Types and brewing methods == There are many different types of sake, such as Shiroki, Kuroki, Sumizake, and Nigorizake, and many different brewing methods. The "ki" in "baijiu" and "kuroki" is the old name for sake, and is also written "baijiu" and "kurokiu. Black liquor is also called "kuro-miki.<ref>{{Cite web|last=日本国語大辞典|first=精選版|title=黒御酒とは|url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E9%BB%92%E5%BE%A1%E9%85%92-253648|access-date=2022-02-26|website=コトバンク|language=ja}}</ref>
